I'd be happy to provide a practical example of how to set up a text input form that saves entries using a simple Node.js and Express.js backend. This example will give you a starting point to build upon and adapt to your specific needs.

**Example: Text Input Form with Node.js and Express.js**

**Step 1: Set up a new Node.js project**

Create a new directory for your project and initialize a new Node.js project using `npm init`. Install the required dependencies, including Express.js and a database driver (e.g., `mysql` or `mongodb`).

**Step 2: Create a text input form**

Create a new file called `index.html` and add the following code to create a simple text input form:
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
  <head>
    <title>Text Input Form</title>
  </head>
  <body>
    <h1>Text Input Form</h1>
    <form id="text-input-form">
      <label for="text-input">Enter your text:</label>
      <textarea id="text-input" name="text"></textarea>
      <button type="submit">Save Text</button>
    </form>
    <script src="script.js"></script>
  </body>
</html>
```
**Step 3: Create a script to handle form submission**

Create a new file called `script.js` and add the following code to handle form submission:
```javascript
const form = document.getElementById('text-input-form');
form.addEventListener('submit', (e) => {
  e.preventDefault();
  const text = document.getElementById('text-input').value;
  fetch('/save-text', {
    method: 'POST',
    headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' },
    body: JSON.stringify({ text }),
  })
    .then((response) => response.json())
    .then((data) => console.log(data))
    .catch((error) => console.error(error));
});
```
**Step 4: Create a Node.js server to handle form submission**

Create a new file called `server.js` and add the following code to create a Node.js server using Express.js:
```javascript
const express = require('express');
const app = express();
const port = 3000;

app.use(express.json());

app.post('/save-text', (req, res) => {
  const text = req.body.text;
  // Save the text to a database or file
  console.log(`Saved text: ${text}`);
  res.json({ message: 'Text saved successfully' });
});

app.listen(port, () => {
  console.log(`Server listening on port ${port}`);
});
```
**Step 5: Run the server and test the form**

Run the server using `node server.js` and open `index.html` in a web browser. Enter some text in the form and click the "Save Text" button. The text should be saved to the console, and you should see a success message in the browser.

This example demonstrates a basic text input form that saves entries to the console. You can adapt this code to save the text to a database or file, and add additional features such as user authentication and validation.

